Stay Safe Online – Cybercrime Prevention Checklist
For College Students in India


1. Verify the sender's email address carefully before clicking any link — phishing emails often use addresses like `noreply@vit-bhopal.support.com` instead of the official domain.

2. Never share OTPs with anyone, including people who claim to be from your bank, university, or telecom provider — no legitimate organisation will ever ask for an OTP over a call or message.

3. Check the URL before entering credentials— always ensure the website address begins with `https://` and matches the official domain exactly.

4. Use unique, strong passwords for each account and enable two-factor authentication (2FA) wherever available, especially for email and banking apps.

5. Do not connect to public/unsecured Wi-Fi for banking, college portal logins, or any sensitive transactions — use mobile data or a trusted VPN instead.

6. UPI Safety never scan a QR code** sent by a stranger claiming to "send you money" — scanning a QR code in UPI apps can authorise a payment FROM you, not to you.

7. UPI Safety set a daily transaction limit on your UPI app (Google Pay, PhonePe, BHIM) and review your transaction history weekly to spot any unauthorised activity early.

8. Download apps only from official sources — Google Play Store or Apple App Store — and check reviews and developer details before installing financial or utility apps.


Reporting Channels

| Channel | Details |
| **National Cyber Crime Portal** | cybercrime.gov.in |
| **Cyber Crime Helpline** | **1930** (available 24x7) |
| **Local Police** | File an FIR at your nearest police station for financial cybercrime |

> If you suspect you have been targeted, act immediately: change your passwords, alert your bank, and call **1930** without delay.
